> What library are you using that depends on the scroll monitor?

One I'm writing (:

I actually am using require in the project I'm working on. However, I don't want my library (a jQuery plugin) to be AMD-aware. (This is the same situation as non-AMD scripts that require jQuery—like underscore or most jQuery plugins.) Since my plugin looks for scrollMonitor on the window object, I would expect to be able to just shim it (as one would with jQuery). However, since scrollMonitor doesn't export itself onto the window object like jQuery, it takes some extra configuration (the `init` function below):

``` javascript
require.config({
    shim: {
        'jquery.myplugin': {
            deps: ['jquery', 'scrollMonitor'],
            init: function ($, scrollMonitor) {
                window.scrollMonitor = scrollMonitor;
            }
        }
    }
});
```

This isn't the end of the world, but it's not exactly the most intuitive thing.

Good point about `scrollTop()`, I'll fix it today or tomorrow.

Sorry about IE support. I've been spoiled by not having to work with legacy IE versions and forgot that they attached events differently. I had a look at MDN and this is what they recommend [here](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/EventTarget.addEventListener):

``` js
if (el.addEventListener) {
  el.addEventListener('click', modifyText, false); 
} else if (el.attachEvent)  {
  el.attachEvent('onclick', modifyText);
}
```

Seems pretty straightforward. But unit tests are good anyway.

Here's the API I think is best. LMK if anyone interested in implementing it in a PR and I can help with a more specific spec with errors, etc.

``` javascript
// create an instance that watches scrolling of a specific element
var containerMonitor = scrollMonitor.createContainer(containerElement);

// create watchers that watch the scrolling of that element
var watcher = containerMonitor.create(childElement);
var watcher2 = containerMonitor.create(otherChildElement);
```

This is the smallest change that could be made to the API, it might even be a minor version since `scrollMonitor.create()` would just reference an instance that watches the window. The watcher creation API is the same if you're creating from the window or a different container. It also makes it simple to clean up after yourself, a .destroy method would remove all listeners from the DOM.

There is a wide consensus that it should only notify you when an element scrolls into its parent, and that the visibility of that parent is irrelevant.

